# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vala-lang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vala-lang/gobject] The **GLib Object System**, or **GObject**, is a free software library providing a portable object system and transparent cross-language interoperability.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] GObject is designed for use both directly in C programs to provide object-oriented C-based APIs and through bindings to other languages to provide transparent cross-language interoperability, e.g.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Depending only on GLib and libc, GObject is a cornerstone of GNOME and is used throughout GTK, Pango, ATK, and most higher-level GNOME libraries like GStreamer and applications.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Prior to GTK+ 2.0, code similar to GObject was part of the GTK codebase.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] At the release of GTK+ 2.0, the object system was extracted into a separate library due to its general utility.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] In the process, most non-GUI-specific parts of the `GtkObject` class were moved up into `GObject`, the new common baseclass.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Having existed as a separate library since March 11, 2002 (the release date of GTK+ 2.0), the GObject library is now used by many non-GUI programs such as command-line and server applications.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Though GObject has its own separate set of documentation and is usually compiled into its own shared library file, the source code for GObject resides in the GLib source tree and is distributed along with GLib.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] For this reason, GObject uses the GLib version numbers and is typically packaged together with GLib (for example, Debian puts GObject in its `libglib2.0` package family).
[src:vala-lang/gobject] At the most basic level of the GObject framework lies a generic and dynamic type system called GType.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] The GType system holds a runtime description of all objects allowing glue code to facilitate multiple language bindings.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] The type system can handle any singly inherited class structure, in addition to *non-classed* types such as opaque pointers, strings, and variously sized integers and floating point numbers.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] The type system knows how to copy, assign, and destroy values belonging to any of the registered types.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] This is trivial for types like integers, but many complex objects are reference-counted, while some are complex but not reference-counted.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] When the type system "copies" a reference-counted object, it will typically just increase its reference count, whereas when copying a complex, non-reference-counted object (such as a string), it will typically create an actual copy by allocating memory.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] This basic functionality is used for implementing `GValue`, a type of generic container that can hold values of any type known by the type system.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Such containers are particularly useful when interacting with dynamically typed language environments in which all native values reside in such type-tagged containers.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Types that do not have any associated classes are called *non-classed*.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] These types, together with all types that correspond to some form of root class, are known as *fundamental types*: the types from which all other types are derived.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] These make up a relatively closed set, but although the average user is not expected to create their own fundamental types, the possibility does exist and has been exploited to create custom class hierarchies — i.e., class hierarchies not based on the `GObject` class.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Types that can be instantiated automatically by the type system are called *instantiable*.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] An important characteristic of these types is that the first bytes of any instance always contain a pointer to the *class structure* (a form of virtual table) associated to the type of the instance.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] For this reason, any instantiable type must be classed.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Contrapositively, any non-classed type (such as *integer* or *string*) must be non-instantiable.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] On the other hand, most classed types are instantiable, but some, such as interface types, are not.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] should be registered with the type system.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Some data structures that are too simple to be made full-fledged class types (with all the overhead incurred) may still need to be registered with the type system.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] to represent this structure, and provide functions for copying and freeing.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] GObject ships with a handful of boxed types wrapping simple GLib data types.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Another use for boxed types is as a way to wrap foreign objects in a tagged container that the type system can identify and will know how to copy and free.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Sometimes, for objects that need to be neither copied or reference-counted nor freed, even a boxed type would be overkill.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] ), it is often a good idea to create a derived pointer type, documenting the fact that the pointers should reference a particular kind of object, even though nothing else is said about it.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] The GObject messaging system consists of two complementary parts: *closures* and *signals*.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Support exists for closures written in C and C++, as well as arbitrary languages (when bindings are provided).
[src:vala-lang/gobject] This allows code written in (for example) Python and Java to be invoked via a GObject closure.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Signals are the primary mechanism by which closures are invoked.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Objects register signal listeners with the type system, specifying a mapping between a given signal and a given closure.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Upon emission of a registered signal, that signal's closure is invoked.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] In GTK, all native GUI events (such as mouse motion and keyboard actions) can generate GObject signals for listeners to potentially act upon.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Each GObject class is implemented by at least two structures: the *class structure* and the *instance structure*.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] It must begin with the class structure of the superclass.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Class-specific variables can be used to emulate class members.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] (this ensures that all instances begin with a pointer to the class structure, since all fundamental instantiable types share this property).
[src:vala-lang/gobject] After the data belonging to the superclass, the structure can hold any instance-specific variables, corresponding to C++ member variables.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Defining a class in the GObject framework is complex, requiring large amounts of boilerplate code, such as manual definitions of type casting macros and obscure type registration incantations.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Also, since a C structure cannot have access modifiers like "public", "protected", or "private", workarounds must be used to provide encapsulation.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] One approach is to include a pointer to the private data — conventionally called `_priv` — in the instance structure.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] The *private structure* can be declared in the public header file, but defined only in the implementation file, with the effect that the private data is opaque to users, but transparent to the implementor.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] If the private structure is registered with GType, it will be automatically allocated by the object system.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Indeed, it is not even necessary to include the `_priv` pointer, if one is willing to use the incantation `G_TYPE_INSTANCE_GET_PRIVATE` every time the private data is needed.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] To address some of these complexities, several higher-level languages exist that source-to-source compiles to GObject in C.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] The Vala programming language uses a C#-style syntax and is pre-processed into vanilla C code.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] The GObject Builder, or GOB2, offers a template syntax reminiscent of Java.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] The combination of C and GObject is used in many successful free software projects, such as the GNOME desktop, the GTK toolkit and the GIMP image manipulation program.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Though many GObject applications are written entirely in C, the GObject system maps well into the native object systems of many other languages, like C++, Java, Ruby, Python, Common Lisp, and .NET/Mono.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] As a result, it is usually relatively painless to create language bindings for well-written libraries that use the GObject framework.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] For example, many Python programs use libraries written in C that use the GObject framework by using the PyGObject language binding.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] (A few of them are listed at Category:Software that uses PyGObject).
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Writing GObject code in C in the first place, however, is relatively verbose.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] The library takes a good deal of time to learn, and programmers with experience in high-level object-oriented languages often find it somewhat tedious to work with GObject in C.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] For example, creating a subclass (even just a subclass of `GObject`) can require writing and/or copying large amounts of boilerplate code.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] However, using Vala, a language that is designed primarily to work with GObject and which converts to C, is likely to make working with GObject or writing GObject based libraries nicer.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Although they are not really first-class objects (there are no actual metatypes in GType), metaobjects like classes and interfaces are created by GObject applications at runtime, and provide good support for introspection.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Since GObject provides a mostly complete object system for C, it can be seen as an alternative to C-derived languages such as C++ and Objective-C, though both also offer many other features beyond just their respective object systems.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] An easily observed difference between C++ and GObject is that GObject (like Java) does not support multiple inheritance.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] This tends to work against including GObject in software where resilience in the face of limited memory is important, or where very many or very large objects are commonly handled.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] The g_try_new() can be used when a memory allocation is more likely to fail (for a large object for example), but this cannot grant that the allocation will not fail elsewhere in the code.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Another important difference is that while C++ and Objective-C are separate languages, GObject is strictly a library and as such does not introduce any new syntax or compiler intelligence.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] For example, when writing GObject-based C code, it is frequently necessary to perform explicit upcasting.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Hence, "C with GObject", also called "glib-flavored C", considered as a language separate from plain C, is a strict superset of plain C — like Objective C, but unlike C++.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] On platforms where there is no standard ABI that works across all C++ compilers (which is not usually the case, since either the Itanium ABI or the Microsoft ABI are usually followed), a library compiled with one C++ compiler is not always able to call a library compiled with a different one.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] If such compatibility is required, the C++ methods must be exported as plain C functions, partly defeating the purpose of the C++ object system.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] The problem occurs in part because different C++ compilers use different kinds of name mangling to ensure the uniqueness of all exported symbols.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Hence, despite being object-oriented, a GObject-based library written in C will always use the same external symbol names regardless of which compiler is used.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Perhaps the most profound difference is GObject's emphasis on signals (called events in other languages).
[src:vala-lang/gobject] This emphasis derives from the fact that GObject was specifically designed to meet the needs of a GUI toolkit.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Whilst there are signal libraries for most object-oriented languages out there, in the case of GObject it is built into the object system.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Because of this, a typical GObject application will tend to use signals to a much larger extent than a non-GObject application would, making GObject components much more encapsulated and reusable than the ones using plain C++ or Java.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] If using glibmm/gtkmm, the official C++ wrappers to Glib/GTK respectively, the sibling project libsigc++ allows easy use of underlying GObject signals using standard C++.
[src:vala-lang/gobject] Of course, other implementations of signals are available on almost all platforms, although sometimes an extra library is needed, such as Boost.Signals2 for C++.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] The GTK team releases new versions on a regular basis.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GTK 4 and GTK 3 are actively maintained, while GTK 2 is no longer supported.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GTK 1 is independently maintained by the CinePaint project.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] The GTK library contains a set of graphical control elements (widgets); version 3.22.16 contains 186 active and 36 deprecated widgets.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GTK is an object-oriented widget toolkit written in the programming language C; it uses GObject (that is, the GLib object system) for object orientation.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] While GTK is mainly used with windowing systems based on Wayland (and prior to that on Wayland's predecessor X11), it works on other platforms, including Microsoft Windows (interfaced with the Windows API), and macOS (interfaced with Quartz).
[src:vala-lang/gtk] There is also an HTML5 back-end named *Broadway*, although this was deprecated in 2025 with the X11 backend to indicate both would be removed in GTK version 5.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GTK uses Vulkan or GL to draw most graphical elements.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GTK can be configured to change the look of the widgets drawn with its CSS engine.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] CSS can be used both at the system/user level, for all applications, and set by the application.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GDK acts as a wrapper around the low-level functions provided by the underlying windowing and graphics systems.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GSK is the rendering and scene graph API for GTK.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GSK lies between the graphical control elements (widgets) and the rendering.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GSK was finally merged into GTK version 3.90 released March 2017.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GtkBuilder allows user interfaces to be designed without writing code.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] The interface is described in an Extensible Markup Language (XML) file which is written by hand or generated by a GUI designer, which is then loaded at runtime and the objects created automatically.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] The description of the user interface is independent from the programming language being used.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] Language bindings are available for using GTK from languages other than C, including C++, Genie, JavaScript, Perl, Python, Vala, and others.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GTK supports various backends, which provides different ways to display GTK applications depending on the system and environment.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] There are several GUI designers for GTK.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] The GTK Inspector is a built-in interactive debugging tool in GTK, allowing developers to inspect and modify UI elements, test CSS changes, and analyze widget structure in real time.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] It can be enabled using the `Control + Shift + I` or `Control + Shift + D` shortcuts, or by setting the `GTK_DEBUG=interactive` environment variable.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] It was introduced with GTK version 3.14.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GTK is mainly developed by The GNOME Project, which also develops the GNOME Development Platform and the GNOME Desktop Environment.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GNOME developers and users gather at an annual *GNOME Users And Developers European Conference* GUADEC meeting to discuss GNOME's current state and future direction.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GNOME incorporates standards and programs from freedesktop.org to better interoperate with other desktops.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] Many GNOME applications have been ported to GTK 4, which was released in December 2020, however some still use GTK+ 3 (GIMP being a major one).
[src:vala-lang/gtk] The master branch of GTK utilizes Meson for its build automation.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GTK (and GNOME, GLib, etc.) formerly utilized the GNU Build System (named Autotools) as the build automation system of choice.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] Since August 14, 2017, the Autotools build system files have been dropped.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] The most common criticism of GTK is the lack of backward-compatibility in major updates, most notably in the application programming interface (API) and theming.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] As a result, application and theme developers often have to rewrite parts of their code to ensure compatibility with newer version of GTK.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] The compatibility breaks between minor releases during the GTK 3.x development cycle was explained in 2013 by Benjamin Otte as due to strong pressures to innovate, such as providing the features modern users expect and supporting the increasingly influential Wayland display server protocol.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] With the release of GTK 4, the pressure from the need to innovate will have been released and the balance between stability and innovation will tip toward stability.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] Similarly, recent changes to theming are specifically intended to improve and stabilise that part of the API, meaning some investment now should be rewarded later.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] However, in 2025, GTK 5 is described in the official documentation as "a major new version of GTK that breaks both API and ABI compared to GTK 4.x.", like GTK 3 and 4.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GTK programs can be run on desktop environments based on X11 and Wayland, or others including ones not made with GTK, provided the needed libraries are installed; this includes macOS if X11.app is installed.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GTK can be also run on Microsoft Windows.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] It is used by some popular cross-platform applications like Pidgin and GIMP. wxWidgets, a cross-platform GUI toolkit, uses GTK on Linux by default.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] Other ports include DirectFB (for example used by the Debian installer).
[src:vala-lang/gtk] Several desktop environments utilize GTK as the widget toolkit.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] For syntax highlighting there is GtkSourceView, "source code editing widget".
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GtkSourceView is maintained by GNOME separately from GTK as a library: gtksourceview.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GtkSpell is a library separate from GTK.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] Enchant is a wrapper for ispell, hunspell, etc., the actual spell checker engine/software.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GtkSpell uses GTK's GtkTextView widget, to highlight misspelled words and offer replacement.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] Finally GTK was re-written to be object-oriented and was renamed GTK+.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] This was first used in the 0.99 release of GIMP.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GTK was subsequently adopted for maintenance by the GNOME Foundation, which uses it in the GNOME desktop environment.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] The GTK 2.0.0 release (2002) series introduced new features which include improved text rendering using Pango, a new theme engine, improved accessibility using the Accessibility Toolkit, transition to Unicode using UTF-8 strings, and a more flexible API.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] Starting with version 2.8, released in 2005, GTK 2 depends on the Cairo graphics library for rendering vector graphics.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GTK version 3.0.0 (2011) included revised input device handling, support for themes written with CSS-like syntax, and the ability to receive information about other opened GTK applications.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] The '+' was dropped returning to simply 'GTK' in February 2019 during a Hackathon.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] Release of the first GTK 4 version was in December 2020.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] At the 2018 edition of DevConf.cz, Matthias Clasen gave an overview of the then-current state of GTK 4 development, including a high-level explanation of how rendering and input worked in GTK 3, what changes were being made to GTK 4, and the reasons for those changes.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] Examples of things that have become possible with GTK 4 were given as well.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] One of the main changes made during the GTK 4 development cycle (i.e.
[src:vala-lang/gtk] GTK 3.92, etc.) was the removal of user customization options (like individual keyboard shortcuts that could be set in GTK+ 2), and the delegation of functionality to ancillary objects instead of encoding it into the base classes provided by GTK.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Vala is syntactically similar to C# and includes notable features such as anonymous functions, signals, properties, generics, assisted memory management, exception handling, type inference, and foreach statements.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Its developers, Jürg Billeter and Raffaele Sandrini, wanted to bring these features to the plain C runtime with little overhead and no special runtime support by targeting the GObject object system.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Rather than compiling directly to machine code or assembly language, it compiles to a lower-level intermediate language.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] It transpiles to C, which is then compiled with a C compiler for a given platform, such as GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) or Clang.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Using functions from native code libraries requires writing vapi files, defining the library interfaces.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Writing these interface definitions is well-documented for C libraries.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Bindings are already available for many libraries, including some not based on GObject such as the multimedia library Simple DirectMedia Layer (SDL) and OpenGL.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Vala is a programming language that combines the high-level build-time performance of scripting languages with the run-time performance of low-level programming languages.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] It aims to bring modern programming language features to GNOME without imposing added runtime requirements and without using a different application binary interface (ABI), compared to applications and libraries written in C.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] The syntax of Vala is similar to C#, modified to better fit the GObject type system.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Vala was conceived by Jürg Billeter and was implemented by him and Raffaele Sandrini, who wished for a higher-level alternative for developing GNOME applications instead of C.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] They liked the syntax and semantics of C# but did not want to use Mono, so they finished a compiler in May 2006.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Initially, it was bootstrapped using C, and one year later (with release of version 0.1.0 in July 2007), the Vala compiler became self-hosted.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] In 2008, the Genie language was created to expose a Python-like syntax to the Vala compiler.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] As of 2021, the current stable release branch with long-term support is 0.48, and the language is under active development with the goal of releasing a stable version 1.0.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Vala uses GLib and its submodules (GObject, GModule, GThread, GIO) as the core library, which is available for most operating systems and offers things like platform independent threading, input/output, file management, network sockets, plugins, regular expressions, etc.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Graphical user interfaces can be developed with the GTK GUI toolkit and the Glade GUI builder.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] For memory management, the GType or GObject system provides reference counting.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] In C, a programmer must manually manage adding and removing references, but in Vala, managing such reference counts is automated if a programmer uses the language's built-in reference types rather than plain pointers.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] The only detail one needs to worry about is to avoid generating reference cycles, because in that case this memory management system will not work correctly.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Vala also allows manual memory management with pointers as an option.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Vala is intended to provide runtime access to existing C libraries, especially GObject-based libraries, without the need for runtime bindings.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] To use a library with Vala, all that is needed is an API file (.vapi) containing the class and method declarations in Vala syntax.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] However, C++ libraries are not supported.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] At present, vapi files for a large part of the GNU project and GNOME platform are included with each release of Vala, including GTK.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] There is also a library named Gee, written in Vala, that provides GObject-based interfaces and classes for commonly used data structures.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] It should also be easily possible to write a bindings generator for access to Vala libraries from applications written in other languages, e.g., C#, as the Vala parser is written as a library, so that all compile-time information is available when generating a binding.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Tooling for Vala development has seen significant improvement over the recent years.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Currently, there are a number of build systems supporting Vala, including Automake, CMake, Meson, and others.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Debugging for Vala programs can be done with either GDB or LLDB.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] As can be noted, unlike C or C++, there are no header files in Vala.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] The linking to libraries is done by specifying `--pkg` parameters during compiling.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Moreover, the GLib library is always linked and its namespace can be omitted (`print` is in fact `GLib.print`).
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Below is a more complex version which defines a subclass `HelloWorld` inheriting from the base class `GLib.Object`, aka the GObject class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] As in the case of GObject library, Vala does not support multiple inheritance, but a class in Vala can implement any number of interfaces, which may contain default implementations for their methods.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Below is a basic example to show a signal defined in a class that is not compact, which has a signal system built in by Vala through GLib.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] Then callback functions are registered to the signal of an instance of the class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] A new thread in Vala is a portion of code such as a function that is requested to be executed concurrently at runtime.
[src:vala-lang/vala-programming-language] The statement `Gtk.main()` creates and starts a main loop listening for events, which are passed along via signals to the callback functions.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Disclaimer: Vala is an ongoing project, and its features may change.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] I will try to keep this tutorial as up to date as I can, but I'm not perfect.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Also, I can't promise that the techniques which I suggest are necessarily the best in practice, but again I will try to keep up with that sort of thing.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala is a new programming language that allows modern programming techniques to be used to write applications that run on the GNOME runtime libraries, particularly GLib and GObject.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This platform has long provided a very complete programming environment, with such features as a dynamic type system and assisted memory management.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Before Vala, the only ways to program for the platform were with the machine native C API, which exposes a lot of often unwanted detail, with a high level language that has an attendant virtual machine, such as Python or the Mono C# language, or alternatively, with C++ through a wrapper library.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala is different from all these other techniques, as it outputs C code which can be compiled to run with no extra library support beyond the GNOME platform.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This has several consequences, but most importantly: Programs written in Vala should have broadly similar performance to those written directly in C, whilst being easier and faster to write and maintain.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A Vala application can do nothing that a C equivalent cannot.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Whilst Vala introduces a lot of language features that are not available in C, these are all mapped to C constructs, although they are often ones that are difficult or too time consuming to write directly.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] As such, whilst Vala is a modern language with all of the features you would expect, it gains its power from an existing platform, and must in some ways comply with the rules set down by it.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This tutorial will not go into depth about basic programming practices.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] It will only briefly explain the principles of object-oriented programming, instead focusing on how Vala applies the concepts.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] As such it will be helpful if you have experience of a variety of programming languages already, although in-depth knowledge of any particular one is not required.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala shares a lot of syntax with C#, but I will try to avoid describing features in terms of their similarity or differences with either C# or Java, with the aim of making the tutorial more accessible.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] What will be useful is a reasonable understanding of C.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Whilst this isn't needed for understanding Vala per se, it is important to realise that Vala programs are executed as C, and will often interact with C libraries.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Knowledge of C will certainly make a deeper understanding of Vala far easier to come by.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Code will be in monospaced text, commands will all be prefaced with a $ prompt.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Other than that, everything should be obvious.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] I tend to code very explicitly, including some information that is actually implied.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] I will try to explain where some things can be omitted, but that doesn't mean that I encourage you do to this.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] At some point I will add in references to the Vala documentation, but that isn't really possible yet.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Of course, that is a Vala *Hello World* program.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] I expect you can recognise some parts of it well enough, but just to be thorough I shall go through it step by step.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This line identifies the beginning of a class definition.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Classes in Vala are very similar in concept to other languages.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A class is basically a type of object, of which instances can be created, all having the same properties.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The implementation of classed types is taken care of by the *gobject* library, but details of this are not important for general usage.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] What is important to note is that this class is specifically described as being a subclass of *GLib.Object*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This is because Vala allows other types of class, but in most cases, this is the sort that you want.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In fact, some language features of Vala are only allowed if your class is descended from GLib's *Object*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Other parts of this line show namespacing and fully qualified names, although these will be explained later.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This is the start of a method definition.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A method is a function related to a type of object that can be executed on an object of that type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The static method means that the method can be called without possessing a particular instance of the type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The fact that this method is called *main* and has the signature it does means that Vala will recognise it as the entry point for the program.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The *main* method doesn't have to be defined inside a class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] However, if it is defined inside a class it must be static.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] It doesn't matter if it's public or private.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The return type may be either int or void.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] With a void return type the program will implicitly terminate with exit code 0.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The string array parameter holding the command line arguments is optional.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] return is to return a value to the caller and terminate the execution of the *main* method which also terminates the execution of the program.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The returned value of the *main* method is then taken as the exit code of the program.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The last lines simply end the definitions of the method and class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] If you get some warnings from a C language compiler, please jump to Valac for the reason and solution.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala code is written in files with *.vala* extensions.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala does not enforce as much structure as a language like Java - there are no concepts of packages or class files in the same way.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Instead structure is defined by text inside each file, describing the logical location of the code with constructs such as namespaces.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] When you want to compile Vala code, you give the compiler a list of the files required, and Vala will work out how they fit together.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The upshot of all this is that you can put as many classes or functions into a file as you want, even combining parts of different namespaces in together.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] There are certain conventions you probably want to follow.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A good example of how to structure a project in Vala is the Vala project itself.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] All source files for the same package are supplied as command line parameters to the Vala compiler valac, along with compiler flags.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This works similarly to how Java source code is compiled.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] will produce a binary with the name *compiler* that links with the package *libvala*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In fact, this is how the *valac* compiler is produced!
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] If you give *valac* the -C switch, it won't compile your program into a binary file.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Instead it will output the intermediate C code for each of your Vala source files into a corresponding C source file, in this case *source1.c* and *source2.c*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] If you look at the content of these files you can see that programming a class in Vala is equivalent to the same task in C, but a whole lot more succinct.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] You will also notice that this class is registered dynamically in the running system.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This is a good example of the power of the GNOME platform, but as I've said before, you do not need to know much about this to use Vala.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala's syntax is an amalgam heavily based on C#'s.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] As a result, most of this will be familiar to programmers who know any C-like language, and in light of this I have kept things brief.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] An object or reference is only valid between { and }.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] These are also the delimiters used to define classes, methods, code blocks etc, so they automatically have their own scope.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala is not strict about where variables are declared.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] An identifier is defined by its type and a name, e.g. int c meaning an integer called *c*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In the case of value types this also creates an object of the given type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] For reference types these just define a new reference that doesn't initially point to anything.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Identifier names may be any combination of letters ([a-z], [A-Z]), underscores and digits.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] However, to define or refer to an identifier with a name that either starts with a digit or is a keyword, you must prefix it with the '@' character.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This character is not considered a part of the name.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] For example, you can name a method *foreach* by writing @foreach, even though this is a reserved Vala keyword.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] You can omit the '@' character when it can be unambiguously interpreted as an identifier name, such as in "foo.foreach()".
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Reference types are instantiated using the new operator and the name of a construction method, which is usually just the name of the type, e.g.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Object o = new Object() creates a new Object and makes *o* a reference to it.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala allows comments in code in different ways.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] These are handled in the same way as in most other languages and so need little explanation.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Documentation comments are actually not special to Vala, but a documentation generation tool like Valadoc will recognise them.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Broadly speaking there are two types of data in Vala: *reference types* and *value types*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] These names describe how instances of the types are passed around the system - a value type is copied whenever it is assigned to a new identifier, a reference type is not copied, instead the new identifier is simply a new reference to the same object.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A constant is defined by putting const before the type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The naming convention for constants is ALL_UPPER_CASE.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala supports a set of the simple types as most other languages do.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Byte, char, uchar; their names are *char* for historical reasons.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Character, unichar; a 32-bit Unicode character Integer, int, uint Long Integer, long, ulong Short Integer, short, ushort Guaranteed-size Integer, int8, int16, int32, int64 as well as their unsigned siblings uint8, uint16, uint32, uint64.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The numbers indicate the lengths in bits.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Most of these types may have different sizes on different platforms, except for the guaranteed-size integer types.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] You can determine the minimum and maximum values of a numerical type with *.MIN* and *.MAX*, e.g. int.MIN and int.MAX.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala strings are UTF-8 encoded and immutable.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala offers a feature called *verbatim strings*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] These are strings in which escape sequences (such as \n) won't be interpreted, line breaks will be preserved and quotation marks don't have to be masked.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] They are enclosed with triple double quotation marks.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Possible indentations after a line break are part of the string as well.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] string verbatim = """This is a so-called "verbatim string".
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Verbatim strings don't process escape sequences, such as \n, \t, \\, etc.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Strings prefixed with '@' are string templates.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The equality operators == and != compare the content of two strings, contrary to Java's behaviour which in this case would check for referential equality.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] You can slice a string with [start:end].
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Note that indices in Vala start with 0 as in most other programming languages.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] However, you cannot assign a new byte value to this position, since Vala strings are immutable.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] You already know *stdout.printf()* from the *Hello World* example.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Actually, it can take an arbitrary number of arguments of different types, whereas the first argument is a *format string*, following the same rules as C format strings.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] If you must output an error message you can use *stderr.printf()* instead of *stdout.printf()*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In addition the *in* operation can be used to determine whether one string contains another, e.g.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] if ("ere" in "Able was I ere I saw Elba.") ...
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] For more information, please report to the complete overview of the string class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A sample program demonstrating string usage is also available.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] An array is declared by giving a type name followed by [] and created by using the new operator e.g. int[] a = new int[10] to create an array of integers.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The length of such an array can be obtained by the *length* member variable e.g. int count = a.length.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Note that if you write Object[] a = new Object[10] no objects will be created, just the array to store them in.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Slicing an array will result in a reference to the requested data, not a copy.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] However, assigning the slice to an owned variable (as is done above) will result in a copy.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Multi-dimensional arrays are defined with [,] or [,,] etc.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This sort of array is represented by a single contiguous memory block.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Jagged multi-dimensional arrays ([][], also known as "stacked arrays" or "arrays of arrays"), where each row may have a different length, are not yet supported.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] To find the length of each dimension in a multi-dimensional array, the *length* member becomes an array, storing the length of each respective dimension.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] You can append array elements dynamically with the += operator.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] However, this works only for locally defined or private arrays.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The array is automatically reallocated if needed.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Internally this reallocation happens with sizes growing in powers of 2 for run-time efficiency reasons.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] However, .length holds the actual number of elements, not the internal size.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] You can resize an array by calling *resize()* on it.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] It will keep the original content (as much as fits).
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] You can move elements within an array by calling *move(src, dest, length)* on it.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The original positions will be filled with 0.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] If you put the square brackets *after* the identifier together with an indication of size you will get a fixed-size array.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Fixed-size arrays are allocated on the stack (if used as local variables) or in-line allocated (if used as fields) and you can't reallocate them later.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala does not do any bounds checking for array access at runtime.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] If you need more safety you should use a more sophisticated data structure like an *ArrayList*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] You will learn more about that later in the section about *collections*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The reference types are all types declared as a class, regardless of whether they are descended from GLib's *Object* or not.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala will ensure that when you pass an object by reference the system will keep track of the number of references currently alive in order to manage the memory for you.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The value of a reference that does not point anywhere is null.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] More on classes and their features in the section about object oriented programming.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In Vala, you can cast a variable from one type to another.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] For a static type cast, a variable is casted by the desired type name with parenthesis.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A static cast doesn't impose any runtime type safety checking.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala supports another casting mechanism called *dynamic cast* which performs runtime type checking and is described in the section about object oriented programming.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala has a mechanism called *type inference*, whereby a local variable may be defined using var instead of giving a type, so long as it is unambiguous what type is meant.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The type is inferred from the right hand side of the assignment.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Type inference is especially useful for types with generic type arguments (more on these later).
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Defining a new type is a matter of derive it from the one you need.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The left operand must be an identifier, and the right must result in a value or reference as appropriate.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] basic arithmetic, applied to left and right operands.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The + operator can also concatenate strings.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] arithmetic operation between left and right operands, where the left must be an identifier, to which the result is assigned.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] increment and decrement operations with implicit assignment.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] These take just one argument, which must be an identifier of a simple data type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The value will be changed and assigned back to the identifier.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] These operators may be placed in either prefix or postfix positions - with the former the evaluated value of the statement will be the newly calculated value, with the latter the original value is returned.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] bitwise operations: or, exclusive or, and, not.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The second set include assignment and are analogous to the arithmetic versions.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] These can be applied to any of the simple value types.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] (There is of no assignment operator associated with ~ because this is a unary operator.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The equivalent operation is just a = ~a).
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] bit shift operations, shifting the left operand a number of bits according the right operand.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The left operand must be an identifier, to which the result is assigned.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Evaluates to a bool value dependent on whether the left and right operands are equal.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In the case of value types this means their values are equal, in the case of reference types that the objects are the same instance.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] An exception to this rule is the string type, which is tested for equality by value.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Evaluate to a bool value dependent on whether the left and right operands are different in the manner described.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] These are valid for simple value data types, and the string type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] For strings these operators compare the lexicographical order.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] These operations can be applied to Boolean values - the first taking just one value the others two.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Evaluates a condition and returns either the value of the left or the right sub-expression based on whether the condition is true or false: *condition* ?
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] null coalescing operator: a ?? b is equivalent to a != null ? a : b.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] checks if the right operand contains the left operand.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This operator works on arrays, strings, collections or any other type that has an appropriate *contains()* method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] For strings it performs a substring search.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] There are extra operators that are valid in the context of lambda declarations and other specific tasks - these are explained in the context they are applicable.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] will decrement *a* repeatedly, checking before each iteration that *a* is greater than *b*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] will decrement *a* repeatedly, checking after each iteration that *a* is greater than *b*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] will initialize *a* to 0, then print *a* repeatedly until *a* is no longer less than 10, incrementing *a* after each iteration.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] will print out each integer in an array, or another iterable collection.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The meaning of "iterable" will be described later.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] All of the four preceding types of loop may be controlled with the keywords break and continue.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A break instruction will cause the loop to immediately terminate, while continue will jump straight to the test part of the iteration.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] executes a particular piece of code based on a set of conditions.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The first condition to match decides which code will execute, if *a* is greater than 0 it will not be tested whether it is less than 0.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Any number of else if blocks is allowed, and zero or one else blocks.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A switch statement runs exactly one or zero sections of code based on the value passed to it.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In Vala there is no fall through between cases, except for empty cases.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In order to ensure this, each non-empty case must end with a break, return or throw statement.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] It is possible to use switch statements with strings.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A note for C programmers: conditions must always evaluate to a Boolean value.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This means that if you want to check a variable for null or 0 you must do this explicitly: if (object != null) { } or if (number != 0) { }.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Functions are called *methods* in Vala, regardless of whether they are defined inside a class or not.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] From now on we will stick to the term *method*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This code defines a method, having the name *method_name*, taking two arguments, one an integer and the other an *Object* (the first passed by value, the second as a reference as described).
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The method will return an integer, which in this case is 1.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] All Vala methods are C functions, and therefore take an arbitrary number of arguments and return one value (or none if the method is declared *void*).
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] They may approximate more return values by placing data in locations known to the calling code.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Details of how to do this are in the "Parameter Directions" section in the advanced part of this tutorial.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The naming convention for methods in Vala is *all_lower_case* with underscores as word separators.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This may be a little bit unfamiliar to C# or Java programmers who are accustomed to *CamelCase* or *mixedCamelCase* method names.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] But with this style you will be consistent with other Vala and C/GObject libraries.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This is due to the fact that libraries produced with Vala are intended to be usable for C programmers as well.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] By choosing slightly different names you can avoid a name clash.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In this case you can use Vala's default argument feature for method parameters in order to achieve a similar behaviour with just one method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] It's even possible to define methods with real variable-length argument lists (*varargs*) like *stdout.printf()*, although not necessarily recommended.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala performs a basic nullability check on the method parameters and return values.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] If it is allowable for a method parameter or a return value to be null, the type symbol should be postfixed with a ? modifier.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This extra information helps the Vala compiler to perform static checks and to add runtime assertions on the preconditions of the methods, which may help in avoiding related errors such as dereferencing a null reference.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In this example text, foo and the return value may be null, however, bar must not be null.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Delegates represent methods, allowing chunks of code to be passed around like objects.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The example above defines a new type named *DelegateType* which represents methods taking an *int* and not returning a value.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Any method that matches this signature may be assigned to a variable of this type or passed as a method argument of this type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This code will execute the method *f2*, passing in a reference to method *f1* and the number 5.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] *f2* will then execute the method *f1*, passing it the number.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] An *anonymous method*, also known as *lambda expression*, *function literal* or *closure*, can be defined in Vala with the => operator.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The parameter list is on the left hand side of the operator, the method body on the right hand side.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] An anonymous method standing by itself like the one above does not make much sense.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] It is only useful if you assign it directly to a variable of a delegate type or pass it as a method argument to another method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Notice that neither parameter nor return types are explicitly given.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Instead the types are inferred from the signature of the delegate it is used with.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In this example *curried_add* (see Currying) returns a newly created method that preserves the value of *a*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This returned method is directly called afterwards with 4 as argument resulting in the sum of the two numbers.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Everything between the braces in this statement is in the namespace *NameSpaceName* and must be referenced as such.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] For example, if the namespace *Gtk* is imported with using Gtk; you can simply write *Window* instead of *Gtk.Window*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A fully qualified name would only be necessary in case of ambiguity, for example between *GLib.Object* and *Gtk.Object*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The namespace *GLib* is imported by default.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Imagine an invisible using GLib; line at the beginning of every Vala file.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Everything that you don't put into a separate namespace will land in the anonymous global namespace.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] If you have to reference the global namespace explicitly due to ambiguity you can do that with the global:: prefix.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Namespaces can be nested, either by nesting one declaration inside another, or by giving a name of the form *NameSpace1.NameSpace2*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Several other types of definition can declare themselves to be inside a namespace by following the same naming convention, e.g. class NameSpace1.Test { ... }.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Note that when doing this, the final namespace of the definition will be the one the declaration is nested in plus the namespaces declared in the definition.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] defines a struct type, i.e. a compound value type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A Vala struct may have methods in a limited way and also may have private members, meaning the explicit public access modifier is required.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Structs are stack/inline allocated and copied on assignment.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] To define an array of structs, please see the FAQ.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In contrast to structs, instances of classes are heap allocated.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] There is much more syntax related to classes, which is discussed more fully in the section about object oriented programming.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] defines an interface, i.e. a non instantiable type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In order to create an instance of an interface you must first implement its abstract methods in a non-abstract class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala interfaces are more powerful than Java or C# interfaces.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The details of interfaces are described in the section about object oriented programming.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Code attributes instruct the Vala compiler details about how the code is supposed to work on the target platform.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Their syntax is [AttributeName] or [AttributeName(param1 = value1, param2 = value2, ...)].
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] They are mostly used for bindings in *vapi* files, [CCode(...)] being the most prominent attribute here.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Another example is the [DBus(...)] attribute for exporting remote interfaces via D-Bus.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Although Vala doesn't force you to work with objects, some features are not available any other way.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] As such, you will certainly want to program in an object-oriented style most of the time.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] As with most current languages, in order to define your own object types, you write a class definition.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A class definition states what data each object of its type has, what other object types it can hold references to, and what methods can be executed on it.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The definition can include a name of another class which the new one should be a subclass of.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] An instance of a class is also an instance of all it's class's super classes, as it inherits from them all their methods and data, although it may not be able to access all of this itself.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A class may also implement any number of interfaces, which are sets of method definitions that must be implemented by the class - an instance of a class is also an instance of each interface implemented by its class or super classes.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Classes in Vala may also have "static" members.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This modifier allows either data or methods to be defined as belonging to the class as a whole, rather than to a specific instance of it.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Such members can be accessed without possessing an instance of the class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This code will define a new type (which is registered automatically with the *gobject* library's type system) that contains three members.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] There are two data members, the integers defined at the top, and one method called *method_1*, which returns an integer.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The class declaration states that this class is a subclass of *GLib.Object*, and therefore instances of it are also *Objects*, and contain all the members of that type also.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The fact that this class is descended from *Object* also means that there are special features of Vala that can be used to easily access some of *Object's* features.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This class is described as public (by default, classes are internal).
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The implication of this is that it can referenced directly by code outside of this file - if you are a C programmer of glib/gobject, you will recognise this as being equivalent to defining the class interfaces in a header file that other code can include.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The members are also all described as either public or private.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The member *first_data* is public, so it is visible directly to any user of the class, and can be modified without the containing instance being aware of it.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The second data member is private, and so can only be referenced by code belonging to this class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala supports four different access modifiers: public No restrictions to access private Access is limited to within the class/struct definition.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The constructor initialises new instances of a class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] It has the same name as the class, may take zero or more arguments and is defined without return type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The final part of this class is a method definition.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This method is to be called *method_1*, and it will return an integer.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] As this method is not static, it can only be executed on an instance of this class, and may therefore access members of that instance.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] It can do this through the this reference, which always points to the instance the method is being called on.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Unless there is an ambiguity, the this identifier can be omitted if wished.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala supports two slightly different construction schemes: the Java/C#-style construction scheme which we will focus on for now, and the GObject-style construction scheme which will be described in a section at the end of the chapter.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Vala does not support constructor overloading for the same reasons that method overloading is not allowed, which means a class may not have multiple constructors with the same name.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] However, this is no problem because Vala supports *named constructors*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Although Vala manages the memory for you, you might need to add your own destructor if you choose to do manual memory management with pointers (more on that later) or if you have to release other resources.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Since Vala's memory management is based on *reference counting* instead of *tracing garbage collection*, destructors are deterministic and can be used to implement the RAII pattern for resource management (closing streams, database connections, ...).
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Signals are a system provided by the Object class in GLib, and made easily accessible by Vala to all descendants of Object.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A signal is recognisable to C# programmers as an event, or to Java programmers as an alternative way of implementing event listeners.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In short, a signal is simply a way of executing an arbitrary number of externally identical methods (i.e. ones with the same signature) at approximately the same time.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The actual methods of execution are internal to *gobject*, and not important to Vala programs.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A signal is defined as a member of a class, and appears similar to a method with no body.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Signal handlers can then be added to the signal using the connect() method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This code introduces a new class called "Test", using familiar syntax.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The first member of this class is a signal, called "sig_1", which is defined as passing an integer.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In the main method of this program, we first create a Test instance - a requirement since signals always belong to instances of classes.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Next, we assign to our instance's "sig_1" signal a handler, which we define inline as a lambda expression.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The definition states that the method will receive two arguments which we call "t" and "a", but do not provide types for.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] We can be this terse because Vala already knows the definition of the signal and can therefore understand what types are required.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The reason there are two parameters to the handler is that whenever a signal is emitted, the object on which it is emitted is passed as the first argument to the handler.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The second argument is that one that the signal says it will provide.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Finally, we get impatient and decide to emit a signal.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] We do this by calling the signal as though it was a method of our class, and allow gobject to take care of forwarding the message to all attached handlers.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Understanding the mechanism used for this is not required to use signals from Vala.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] NB: Currently the public access modifier is the only possible option - all signals can be both connected to and emitted by any piece of code.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] It is good object oriented programming practice to hide implementation details from the users of your classes (information hiding principle), so you can later change the internals without breaking the public API.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] One practice is to make fields private and provide accessor methods for getting and setting their values (getters and setters).
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] The problem is that these methods are cumbersome to work with.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This syntax should be familiar to C# programmers.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] A property has a get and a set block for getting and setting its value. value is a keyword that represents the new value that should be assigned to the property.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Now you can access the property as if it was a public field.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] But behind the scenes the code in the get and set blocks is executed.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] With properties you can change the internal working of classes without changing the public API.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This time the age is calculated on the fly from the year of birth.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Note that you can do more than just simple variable access or assignment within the get and set blocks.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] You could do a database access, logging, cache updates, etc.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Properties may not only have a name but also a short description (called *nick*) and a long description (called *blurb*).
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Properties and their additional descriptions can be queried at runtime.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Some programs such as the Glade graphical user interface designer make use of this information.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In this way Glade can present human readable descriptions for properties of GTK+ widgets.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Every instance of a class derived from GLib.Object has a signal called notify.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This signal gets emitted every time a property of its object changes.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] s is the source of the signal (obj in this example), p is the property information of type *ParamSpec* for the changed property.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] Note that in this case you must use the string representation of the property name where underscores are replaced by dashes: my_property_name becomes "my-property-name" in this representation, which is the GObject property naming convention.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] There's another type of properties called *construct properties* that are described later in the section about gobject-style construction.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This way, c is an reference instead of an instance of Color on stack.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] What you passed into s.get() is "Color **" instead of "Color *".
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In Vala, a class may derive from one or zero other classes.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] In practice this is always likely to be one, although there is no implicit inheritance as there is in languages like Java.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] When defining a class that inherits from another, you create a relationship between the classes where instances of the subclass are also instances of the superclass.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] This means that operations on instances of the superclass are also applicable on instances of the subclass.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] As such, wherever an instance of the superclass is required, an instance of the subclass can be substituted.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p01] When writing the definition of a class it is possible to exercise precise control over who can access what methods and data in the object.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Given these definitions, an instance of *SubClass* will contain all three members of *SuperClass*, but will only be able to access the non-private members.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] External code will only be able to access the public method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] With base a constructor of a subclass can chain up to a constructor of its base class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] There is another modifier for methods, called abstract.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This modifier allows you to describe a method that is not actually implemented in the class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Instead, it must be implemented by subclasses before it can be called.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This allows you to define operations that can be called on all instances of a type, whilst ensuring that all more specific types provide their own version of the functionality.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] A class containing abstract methods must be declared abstract as well.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The result of this is to prevent any instantiation of the type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The implementation of an abstract method must be marked with override.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] A virtual method allows to define default implementations to abstract classes and allows to derived classes to override its behavior, this is different than hiding methods.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] As you can see in the above example, Caller is an abstract class defining both an abstract property and a method, but adds a virtual method which can be overridden by derived classes.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Contact class implements abstract methods and properties of Caller, while using the default implementation for reset() by avoiding to define a new one.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] ContactCV class implements all abstract definitions on Caller, but overrides reset() so as to define its own implementation.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] A class in Vala may implement any number of interfaces.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Each interface is a type, much like a class, but one that cannot be instantiated.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] By "implementing" one or more interfaces, a class may declare that its instances are also instances of the interface, and therefore may be used in any situation where an instance of that interface is expected.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The procedure for implementing an interface is the same as for inheriting from classes with abstract methods in - if the class is to be useful it must provide implementations for all methods that are described but not yet implemented.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This code describes an interface "ITest" which requires GLib.Object as parent of the implementor class and contains two members.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] "data_1" is a property, as described above, except that it is declared abstract.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Vala will therefore not implement this property, but instead require that classes implementing this interface have a property called "data_1" that has both get and set accessors - it is required that this be abstract as an interface may not have any data members.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The second member "method_1" is a method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Here it is declared that this method must be implemented by classes that implement this interface.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Interfaces in Vala may not inherit from other interfaces, but they may declare other interfaces to be prerequisites, which works in roughly the same way.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] For example, it may be desirable to say that any class that implements a List interface must also implement a Collection and Traversable interfaces.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Vala interfaces may also have a class as a prerequisite.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] If a class name is given in the list of prerequisites, the interface may only be implemented in classes that derive from that prerequisite class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This is often used to ensure that an instance of an interface is also a GLib.Object subclass, and so the interface can be used, for example, as the type of a property.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The fact that interfaces can not inherit from other interfaces is mostly only a technical distinction - in practice Vala's system works the same as other languages in this area, but with the extra feature of prerequisite classes.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] There's another important difference between Vala interfaces and Java/C# interfaces: Vala interfaces may have non-abstract methods.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Vala actually allows method implementations in interfaces, then a method with a default implementation must be declared as virtual.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Due to this fact Vala interfaces can act as mixins.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This is a restricted form of multiple inheritance.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Interface Callable defines an abstract property called answering, where any class implementing this interface can monitor the state of a call, details about answer a call is a mautter of the implementator, but hang defines a default implementation to set answering to false when hanging a call.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] When compiling and running, you will find that Phone class actually no implements Callable.hang() method, but it is able to use it, then the result is a message Hang done.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In this case TechPhone is another implementation to Callable, then when hang() method is called on an instance of TechPhone it will always return false and print the message TechPhone.hang () implementation!, hidding completelly Callable.hang() default implementation.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] An interface can define properties that must be implemented for classes.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Implementator class must define a property with the same signature and access permissions to the property's get and set.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] As any GObject property, you can define a body to property's set and get in the implementator class, when no body is used values are set and get by default.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] If given, you must define a private field to store the properties values to be used outside or inside the class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Callable interface definition, defines an answering property.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In this case this interface defines a answering with a protected set, allowing a read only property for any object using an instance of Callable, but allows class implementors to write values to it, like TechPhone class does when implements hang() method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] As described above, Vala while it is backed by C and GObject, can provide a limited multiple inheritance mechanism, by adding virtual methods to Interfaces.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Is possible to add some ways to define default method implementations in interface implementor class and allow derived classes to override that methods.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] If you define a virtual method in an interface and implement it in a class, you can't override interface's method without leaving derived classes unable to access to interface default one.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In this case, we have defined a Callable interface with a default implementation for abstract bool hang () called default_hang, it could be a static or virtual method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Then Caller is a base class implementing Callable for the TechPhone and Phone classes, while Caller's hang () method simple call Callable default implementation.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] TechPhone doesn't do anything and just takes Caller as base class, using the default method implementations; but Phone overrides Caller.hang () and this makes to use its own implementation, allowing to always call it even if it is cast to Callable object.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The explicit interface method implementation allows to implement two interfaces that have methods (not properties) with the same name.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] A logical extension of this power is to allow a subtype to behave differently to its parent type when addressed in exactly the same way.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] These two classes both implement a method called "method_1", and "SubClass" therefore contains two methods called "method_1", as it inherits one from "SuperClass".
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This will actually result in two different methods being called.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The second line believes "o1" to be a "SubClass" and will call that class's version of the method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The fourth line believes "o2" to be a "SuperClass" and will call that class's version of the method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The problem this example exposes, is that any code holding a reference to "SuperClass" will call the methods actually described in that class, even in the actual object is of a subclass.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The way to change this behaviour is using virtual methods.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] When this code is used in the same way as before, "SubClass"'s "method_1" will be called twice.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This is because we have told the system that "method_1" is a virtual method, meaning that if it is overridden in a subclass, that new version will always be executed on instances of that subclass, regardless of the knowledge of the caller.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This distinction is probably familiar to programmers of some languages, such as C++, but it is in fact the opposite of Java style languages, in which steps must be taken to prevent a method being virtual.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] You will probably now also have recognised that when method is declared as abstract it must also be virtual.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Otherwise, it would not be possible to execute that method given an apparent instance of the type it was declared in.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] When implementing an abstract method in a subclass, you may therefore choose to declare the implementation as override, thus passing on the virtual nature of the method, and allowing subtypes to do the same if they desire.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] It's also possible to implement interface methods in such a way that subclasses can change the implementation.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The process in this case is for the initial implementation to declare the method implementation to be virtual, and then subclasses can override as required.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] When writing a class, it is common to want to use functionality defined in a class you have inherited from.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This is complicated where the method name is used more than one in the inheritance tree for your class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] For this Vala provides the base keyword.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The most common case is where you have overridden a virtual method to provide extra functionality, but still need the parent class' method to be called.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] By using the new modifier you can hide an inherited method with a new method of the same name.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The new method may have a different signature.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Method hiding is not to be confused with method overriding, because method hiding does not exhibit polymorphic behaviour.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] With the typeof() operator you can get the type information of a type directly.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] It's the construct {} block that will be described in the section about gobject-style construction.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] For the dynamic cast, a variable is casted by a postfix expression as DesiredTypeName.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Vala will include a runtime type checking to ensure this casting is reasonable - if it is an illegal casting, null will be returned.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] However, this requires both the source type and the target type to be referenced class types.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] If for some reason the class of the widget instance is not the Button class or one of its subclasses or does not implement the Button interface, b will be null.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Vala includes a runtime generics system, by which a particular instance of a class can be restricted with a particular type or set of types chosen at construction time.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This restriction is generally used to require that data stored in the object must be of a particular type, for example in order to implement a list of objects of a certain type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In that example, Vala would make sure that only objects of the requested type could be added to the list, and that on retrieval all objects would be cast to that type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In Vala, generics are handled while the program is running.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] When you define a class that can be restricted by a type, there still exists only one class, with each instance customised individually.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This is in contrast to C++ which creates a new class for each type restriction required - Vala's is similar to the system used by Java.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This has various consequences, most importantly: that static members are shared by the type as a whole, regardless of the restrictions placed on each instance; and that given a class and a subclass, a generic refined by the subclass can be used as a generic refined by the class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This "Wrapper" class must be restricted with a type in order to instantiate it - in this case the type will be identified as "G", and so instances of this class will store one object of "G" type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In order to instantiate this class, a type must be chosen, for example the built in string type (in Vala there is no restriction on what type may be used in a generic).
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] As you can see, when the data is retrieved from the wrapper, it is assigned to an identifier with no explicit type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This is possible because Vala knows what sort of objects are in each wrapper instance, and therefore can do this work for you.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] class TestClass : GLib.Object { } void accept_object_wrapper(Wrapper<Glib.Object> w) { } ... var test_wrapper = new Wrapper<TestClass>(); accept_object_wrapper(test_wrapper); ...
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Since all Test Class instances are also Objects, the "accept_object_wrapper" method will happily accept the object it is passed, and treat its wrapped object as though it was a GLib.Object instance.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] As pointed out before, Vala supports an alternative construction scheme that is slightly different to the one described before, but closer to the way GObject construction works.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Which one you prefer depends on whether you come from the GObject side or from the Java or C# side.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The gobject-style construction scheme introduces some new syntax elements: *construct properties*, a special Object(...) call and a construct block.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] With the gobject-style construction scheme each construction method only contains an Object(...) call for setting so-called *construct properties*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The Object(...) call takes a variable number of named arguments in the form of property: value.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] These properties must be declared as construct or set properties.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] They will be set to the given values and afterwards all construct {} blocks in the hierarchy from *GLib.Object* down to our class will be called.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The construct block is guaranteed to be called when an instance of this class is created, even if it is created as a subtype.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] It does neither have any parameters, nor a return value.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Within this block you can call other methods and set member variables as needed.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Construct properties are defined just as get and set properties, and therefore can run arbitrary code on assignment.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] If you need to do initialisation based on a single construct property, it is possible to write a custom construct block for the property, which will be executed immediately on assignment, and before any other construction code.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] If a construct property is declared without set it is a so-called *construct only* property, which means it can only be assigned on construction, but no longer afterwards.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In the example above *name* is such a construct only property.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In some cases you may also want to perform some action - not when instances of a class is created - but when the class itself is created by the GObject runtime.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In GObject terminology we are talking about a snippet of code run inside the class_init function for the class in question.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In Java this is known as *static initializer blocks*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] With *assertions* a programmer can check assumptions at runtime.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] If an assertion fails the program will terminate with an appropriate error message.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] You might be tempted to use assertions in order to check method arguments for null.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] However, this is not necessary, since Vala does that implicitly for all parameters that are not marked with ? as being *nullable*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Vala supports basic contract programming features.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] result is a special variable representing the return value.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] GLib has a system for managing runtime exceptions called GError.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Vala translates this into a form familiar to modern programming languages, but its implementation means it is not quite the same as in Java or C#.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] It is important to consider when to use this type of error handling - GError is very specifically designed to deal with recoverable runtime errors, i.e. factors that are not known until the program is run on a live system, and that are not fatal to the execution.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] You should not use GError for problems that can be foreseen, such as reporting that an invalid value has been passed to a method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] If a method, for example, requires a number greater than 0 as a parameter, it should fail on negative values using contract programming techniques such as preconditions or assertions described in the previous section.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Vala errors are so-called *checked exceptions*, which means that errors must get handled at some point.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] However, if you don't catch an error the Vala compiler will only issue a warning without stopping the compilation process.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] All this appears more or less as in other languages, but defining the types of errors allowed is fairly unique.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Errors have three components, known as "domain", "code" and message.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Messages we have already seen, it is simply a piece of text provided when the error is created.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Error domains describe the type of problem, and equates to a subclass of "Exception" in Java or similar.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In the above examples we imagined an error domain called "IOError".
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The third part, the error code is a refinement describing the exact variety of problem encountered.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Each error domain has one or more error codes - in the example there is a code called "FILE_NOT_FOUND".
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The way to define this information about error types is related to the implementation in glib.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] When catching an error, you give the error domain you wish to catch errors in, and if an error in that domain is thrown, the code in the handler is run with the error assigned to the supplied name.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] From that error object you can extract the error code and message as needed.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] If you want to catch errors from more than one domain, simply provide extra catch blocks.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] There is also an optional block that can be placed after a try and any catch blocks, called finally.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This code is to be run always at the end of the section, regardless of whether an error was thrown or any catch blocks were executed, even if the error was in fact no handled and will be thrown again.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This allows, for example, any resources reserved in the try block be freed regardless of any errors raised.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This example has two error domains, both of which can be thrown by the "thrower" method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Catcher can only throw the second type of error, and so must handle the first type if "thrower" throws it.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Finally the "main" method will handle any errors from "catcher".
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] A method in Vala is passed zero or more arguments.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The default behaviour when a method is called is as follows: Any value type parameters are copied to a location local to the method as it executes.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Any reference type parameters are not copied, instead just a reference to them is passed to the method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This behaviour can be changed with the modifiers 'ref' and 'out'.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The treatment of each variable will be: "a" is of a value type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The value will be copied into a new memory location local to the method, and so changes to it will not be visible to the caller.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] "b" is also of a value type, but passed as an out parameter.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In this case, the value is not copied, instead a pointer to the data is passed to the method, and so any change to the method parameter will be visible to the calling code.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] "c" is treated in the same way as "b", the only change is in the signalled intent of the method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The method is passed a reference to the same object as the caller has.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The method can therefore change that object, but if it reassigns to the parameter, that change will not be visible to the caller.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] "p" is of the same type, but passed as an out parameter.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This means that the method will receive a pointer to the reference to the object.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] It may therefore replace the reference with a reference to another object, and when the method returns the caller will instead own a reference to that other object.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] When you use this type of parameter, if you do not assign a new reference to the parameter, it will be set to null.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This case is treated like "p" with the important differences that the method may choose not to change the reference, and may access the object referred to.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Vala will ensure that in this instance "q" actually refers to any object, and is not set to null.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] When setting the value to the out argument "b", Vala will ensure that "b" is not null.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] So you can safely pass null as the second argument of method_1() if you are not interested by this value.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Gee is a library of collection classes, written in Vala.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The classes should all be familiar to users of libraries such as Java's Foundation Classes.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Gee consists of a set of interfaces and various types that implement these in different ways.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] If you want to use Gee in your own application, install the library separately on your system.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Gee can be obtained from http://live.gnome.org/Projects/Libgee.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In order to use the library you must compile your programs with --pkg gee-0.8.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The fundamental types of collection are: Lists: Ordered collections of items, accessible by numeric index.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Sets: Unordered collections of distinct.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Maps: Unordered collection of items, accessible by index of arbitrary type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] All the lists and sets in the library implement the *Collection* interface, and all maps the *Map* interface.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Lists also implement *List* and sets *Set*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] These common interfaces means not only that all collections of a similar type can be used interchangeably, but also that new collections can be written using the same interfaces, and therefore used with existing code.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Also common to every *Collection* type is the *Iterable* interface.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This means that any object in this category can be iterated through using a standard set of methods, or directly in Vala using the foreach syntax.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] All classes and interfaces use the generics system.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This means that they must be instantiated with a particular type or set of types that they will contain.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The system will ensure that only the intended types can be put into the collections, and that when objects are retrieved they are returned as the correct type.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] An ordered list of items of type G backed by a dynamically resizing array.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This type is very fast for accessing data, but potentially slow at inserting items anywhere other than at the end, or at inserting items when the internal array is full.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] A 1:1 map from elements of type K to elements of type V.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The mapping is made by computing a hash value for each key - this can be customised by providing pointers to functions for hashing and testing equality of keys in specific ways.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] For strings and integers the hash and equal functions are detected automatically, objects are distinguished by their references by default.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] You have to provide custom hash and equal functions only if you want to override the default behaviour.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Duplicates are detected by computing a hash value for each key - this can be customised by providing pointers to functions for hashing and testing equality of keys in specific ways.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] You can get a read-only view of a collection via the *read_only_view* property, e.g. my_map.read_only_view.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This will return a wrapper that has the same interface as its contained collection, but will not allow any form of modification, or any access to the contained collection.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Vala recognizes some methods with certain names and signatures and provides syntax support for them.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] For example, if a type has a *contains()* method objects of this type can be used with the in operator.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The following table lists these special methods.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] *T* and *Tn* are only type placeholders in this table and meant to be replaced with real types.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The *Iterator* type can have any name and must implement one of these two protocols: bool next() T get() standard iterator protocol: iterating until *.next()* returns false.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The current element is retrieved via *.get()*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] T? next_value() alternative iterator protocol: If the iterator object has a *.next_value()* function that returns a nullable type then we iterate by calling this function until it returns null.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] A program written in Vala may have more than one thread of execution, allowing it it do more than one thing at a time.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Exactly how this is managed is outside of Vala's scope - threads may be sharing a single processor core or not, depending on the environment.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Note the test at the start of the main method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Originally, UNIX did not have threads, which means some traditional UNIX APIs are problematic in threaded programs.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Using this test could check whether the currnt environment supports threads.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] We create a new thread and it will start immediately.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The first argument is its name,the second one is the content of the new thread.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The generic parameter is the type of value which a thread returns.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The program will still not act as we expected, because we just Without any sort of event loop, a Vala program will terminate when its primary/root/parent thread (the one created to run "main") ends.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In order to control this behaviour, you can allow threads to cooperate.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This can be done powerfully using event loops and asynchronous queues, but in this introduction to threading we will just show the basic capabilities of threads.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The child thread will be killed if its primary/parent thread has finished According to this fact, we should tell the primary thread to wait for child threads to finish, by invoking a method join in module Thread.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Because of the method join, the primary thread has to wait for child thread to finish.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] What's more, it is possible for a thread to tell the system that it currently has no need to execute, and thereby suggest that another thread should be run instead, this is done using the static method *Thread.yield()*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] However, there is no guarantee that this will happen still.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The system is able to decide when threads run, and as such might not allow the new thread to finish before the primary thread is restarted and the program ends.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] All these examples have a potential problem, in that the newly created thread doesn't know the context in which it should run.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In C you would supply the thread creation method with some data, in Vala instead you would normally pass an instance method, instead of a static method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Whenever more than one thread of execution is running simultaneously, there is a chance that data are accessed simultaneously.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This can lead to race conditions, where the outcome depends on when the system decides to switch between threads.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In order to control this situation, you can use the lock keyword to ensure that certain blocks of code will not be interrupted by other threads that need to access the same data.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This class defines two methods, where both need to change the value of "a".
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] If there were no lock statements here, it would be possible for the instructions in these methods to be interweaved, and the resulting change to "a" would be effectively random.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] As there are the lock statements here, Vala will guarantee that if one thread has locked "a", another thread that needs the same lock will have to wait its turn.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In Vala it is only possible to lock members of the object that is executing the code.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This might appear to be a major restriction, but in fact the standard use for this technique should involve classes that are individually responsible for controlling a resource, and so all locking will indeed be internal to the class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Likewise, in above example all accesses to "a" are encapsulated in the class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] GLib includes a system for running an event loop, in the classes around MainLoop.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The purpose of this system is to allow you to write a program that waits for events and responds to them, instead of having to constantly check conditions.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This is the model that GTK+ uses, so that a program can wait for user interaction without having to have any currently running code.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The following program creates and starts a MainLoop, and then attaches a source of events to it.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In this case the source is a simple timer, that will execute the given method after 2000ms.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The method will in fact just stop the main loop, which will in this case exit the program.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] When using GTK+, a main loop will be created automatically, and will be started when you call the `Gtk.main()' method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] This marks the point where the program is ready to run and start accepting events from the user or elsewhere.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The code in GTK+ is equivalent to the short example above, and so you may add event sources in much the same way, although of course you need to use the GTK+ methods to control the main loop.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] A common requirement in GUI programs is to execute some code as soon as possible, but only when it will not disturb the user.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] These send events to the programs main loop, but request they only be dealt with when there is nothing more important to do.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] For more information about event loops, see the GLib and GTK+ documentation.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Asynchronous methods are methods whose execution can be paused and resumed under the control of the programmer.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] They are often used in the main thread of an application where a method needs to wait for an external slow task to complete, but must not stop other processing from happening.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] (For example, one slow operation must not freeze the whole GUI).
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] When the method has to wait, it gives control of the CPU back to its caller (i.e. it *yields*), but it arranges to be called back to resume execution when data becomes ready.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] External slow tasks that async methods might wait for include: waiting for data from a remote server, or waiting for calculations in another thread to complete, or waiting for data to load from a disk drive.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Asynchronous methods are normally used with a GLib main loop running, because idle callbacks are used to handle some of the internal callbacks.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] However under certain conditions async may be used without the GLib main loop, for example if the async methods always yield and Idle.add() is never used.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Asynchronous methods are designed for interleaving the processing of many different long-lived operations within a single thread.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] They do not by themselves spread the load out over different threads.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] However, an async method may be used to control a background thread and to wait for it to complete, or to queue operations for a background thread to process.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Async methods in Vala use the GIO library to handle the callbacks, so must be built with the --pkg=gio-2.0 option.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] An asynchronous method is defined with the async keyword.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The method may take arguments and return a value like any other method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] It may use a yield statement at any time to give control of the CPU back to its caller.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Both forms starts the async method running with the given arguments.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The second form in addition registers an AsyncReadyCallback which is executed when the method finishes.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] The callback takes a source object, obj, and an instance of GAyncResult, res, as arguments.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] In the callback the .end() method should be called to receive the return value of the asynchronous method if it has one.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] If the async method can throw an exception, the .end() call is where the exception arrives and must be caught.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] If the method has out arguments, then these should be omitted from the .begin() call and added to the .end() call instead.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] When an asynchronous method starts running, it takes control of the CPU until it reaches its first yield statement, at which point it returns to the caller.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] When the method is resumed, it continues execution immediately after that yield statement.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p02] Some code elsewhere must now call the stored SourceFunc in order for the method to be resumed.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] If the direct call above is used, then the resumed asynchronous method takes control of the CPU immediately and runs until its next yield before returning to the code that executed callback().
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The Idle.add() method is useful if the callback must be made from a background thread, e.g. to resume the async method after completion of some background processing.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] In both cases, the calling method gives up control of the CPU and does not resume until the called method completes.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The yield statement automatically registers a callback with the called method to make sure that the caller resumes correctly.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The automatic callback also collects the return value from the called method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] When this yield statement executes, control of the CPU first passes to the called method which runs until its first yield and then drops back to the calling method, which completes the yield statement itself, and then gives back control to its own caller.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] See Async Method Samples for examples of different ways that async may be used.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Vala's memory management is based on automatic reference counting.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Each time an object is assigned to a variable its internal reference count is increased by 1, each time a variable referencing an object goes out of scope its internal reference count is decreased by 1.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] If the reference count reaches 0 the object will be freed.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] However, it is possible to form a reference cycle with your data structures.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] For example, with a tree data structure where a child node holds a reference to its parent and vice versa, or a doubly-linked list where each element holds a reference to its predecessor and the predecessor holds a reference to its successor.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] In these cases objects could keep themselves alive simply by referencing to each other, even though they should be freed.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] This topic is explained in detail on this page: Vala's Memory Management Explained.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Normally when creating an object in Vala you are returned a reference to it.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Specifically this means that as well as being passed a pointer to the object in memory, it is also recorded in the object itself that this pointer exists.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Similarly, whenever another reference to the object is created, this is also recorded.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] As an object knows how many references there are to it, it can automatically be removed when needed.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] This is the basis of Vala's memory management.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The reason for this seemingly over complicated example because of the concept of ownership.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] If the Object "o" was not stored in the class, then when the method "get_unowned_ref" returned, "o" would become unowned (i.e. there would be no references to it).
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] If this were the case, the object would be deleted and the method would never return a valid reference.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] If the return value was not defined as unowned, the ownership would pass to the calling code.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The calling code is, however, expecting an unowned reference, which cannot receive the ownership.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Vala will try to either obtain a reference of or a duplicate of the instance the unowned reference pointing to.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] In contrast to normal methods, properties always have unowned return value.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] That means you can't return a new object created within the get method.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] That also means, you can't use an owned return value from a method call.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The somewhat irritating fact is because of that a property value is owned by the object that HAS this property.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] A call to obtain this property value should not steal or reproduce (by duplicating, or increasing the reference count of) the value from the object side.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The unowned modifier can be used to make automatic property's storage unowned.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The keyword owned can be used to specifically ask a property to return a owned reference of the value, therefore causing the property value be reproduced in the object side.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Think twice before adding the owned keyword.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Is it a property or simply a get_xxx method?
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] There may also be problems in your design.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Unowned references play a similar role to pointers which are described later.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] They are however much simpler to use than pointers, as they can be easily converted to normal references.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] However, in general they should not be widely used in the programs unless you know what you are doing.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The keyword owned is used to transfer ownership.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] As a prefix of a parameter type, it means that ownership of the object is transferred into this code context.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] As an type conversion operator, it can be used to avoid duplicating non-reference counting classes, which is usually impossible in Vala.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] This means that *bar* will be set to *null* and *foo* inherits the reference/ownership of the object *bar* references.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Vala supports C-style variable-length argument lists ("varargs") for methods.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] They are declared with an ellipsis ("...") in the method signature.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] In this example x is a fixed argument to meet the requirements.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] You obtain the varargs list with va_list().
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Then you can retrieve the arguments one after another by calling the generic method arg<T>() sequently on this list, with T being the type that the argument should be interpreted as.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] If the type is evident from the context (as in our example) the type is inferred automatically and you can just call arg() without the generic type argument.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] It checks for *null* as a sentinel to recognize the end of the varargs list.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Vala always implicitly passes *null* as the last argument of a varargs method call.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Varargs have a serious drawback that you should be aware of: they are not type-safe.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The compiler can't tell you whether you are passing arguments of the right type to the method or not.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] That's why you should consider using varargs only if you have a good reason, for example: providing a convenience function for C programmers using your Vala library, binding a C function.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Often an array argument is a better choice.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] A common pattern with varargs is to expect alternating *string - value* pairs as arguments, usually meaning *gobject property - value*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Pointers are Vala's way of allowing manual memory management.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Normally when you create an instance of a type you receive a reference to it, and Vala will take care of destroying the instance when there are no more references left to it.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] By requesting instead a pointer to an instance, you take responsibility for destroying the instance when it is no longer wanted, and therefore get greater control over how much memory is used.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] This functionality is not necessarily needed most of the time, as modern computers are usually fast enough to handle reference counting and have enough memory that small inefficiencies are not important.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The times when you might resort to manual memory management are: When you specifically want to optimise part of a program and unowned references are insufficient.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The usage of reference-type pointers is equivalent to the use of unowned references.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Classes defined as not being descended from *GLib.Object* are treated as a special case.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] They are derived directly from GLib's type system and therefore much lighter in weight.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] In a more recent Vala compiler, one can also implement interfaces, signals and properties with these classes.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] One obvious case of using these non-*Object* classes stays in the GLib bindings.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Because GLib is at a lower level than GObject, most classes defined in the binding are of this kind.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Also, as mentioned before, the lighter weight of non-object classes make them useful in many practical situations (e.g. the Vala compiler itself).
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] However the detailed usage of non-*Object* classes are outside the scope of this tutorial.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Be aware that these classes are fundamentally different from structs.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] D-Bus is tightly integrated into the language and has never been easier than with Vala.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] To export a custom class as a D-Bus service you just need to annotate it with the *DBus* code attribute and register an instance of this class with your local D-Bus session.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] All member names are automatically mangled from Vala's *lower_case_with_underscores* naming convention to D-Bus *CamelCase* names.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The exported D-Bus interface of this example will have a property *Something*, a signal *Sig1* and a method *SomeMethod*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] You can also use a graphical D-Bus debugger like D-Feet to browse your D-Bus interfaces and call methods.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The generated C code can target a different minimum runtime by using valac's --profile option.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] A profile determines which Vala language features are available to match the minimum runtime environment.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The gobject profile enables code generation that requires GLib's GType runtime type system and so the runtime environment will usually require libgobject and its small number of dependencies.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The libc profile removes the dependency on GLib and disables the runtime type system.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The profile either generates alternative code or errors at compile time if a Vala language feature is used that requires the runtime type system.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] This is useful for writing code that targets microcontrollers or for generating binaries for system utilities or extremely small container images.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The runtime environment will usually require a small subset of the ISO C standard library.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Of course, the binary will still require the runtime dependencies needed for the libraries targeted with valac's --pkg option.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] This means they are not fully tested and might be subject to changes in future versions.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Regular expressions are a powerful technique for pattern matching in strings.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Vala has experimental support for regular expression literals (/regex/).
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The trailing *i* makes the expression case insensitive.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The following trailing characters can be used: *i*, letters in the pattern match both upper- and lowercase letters *m*, the "start of line" and "end of line" constructs match immediately following or immediately before any newline in the string, respectively, as well as at the very start and end.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] *s*, a dot metacharater *.* in the pattern matches all characters, including newlines.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] *x*, whitespace data characters in the pattern are totally ignored except when escaped or inside a character class.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The strict non-null mode helps in avoiding unwanted *null* dereferencing errors.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] This feature would come to full potential if the nullability of all return types in bindings was marked correctly, which is currently not always the case.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] At the system level, a Vala library is exactly a C library, and so the same tools are used.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] In order to make the process simpler, and so that the Vala compiler can understand the process there is then an extra level of Vala specific information.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] A "Vala library" is therefore, the system part: A system library (e.g.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Both of which are installed in the standard locations.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] And the Vala specific files: A VAPI file (e.g.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] *gee-1.0.vapi*) An optional dependency file (e.g.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] These files are explained later in this section.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] It should be noted that the library names are the same in the Vala specific files as in the *pkg-config* files.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Using a library in Vala is largely automated if you use the *valac* compiler.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The Vala specific library files make up what is known as a package.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] This command means your program can use any of the definitions in the *gee-1.0.vapi* file, and also any in any of the packages that *gee-1.0* depends on.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] These dependencies would be be listed in *gee-1.0.deps* if there were any.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] In this example *valac* is set to build all the way to binary, and will therefore incorporate information from *pkg-config* to link the correct libraries.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] This is why the *pkg-config* names are also used for Vala package names.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Packages are generally used with namespaces, but they are not technically related.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] This means that even though your application is built with reference to the package, you must still include the required using statements in each file as appropriate, or else use the fully qualified names of all symbols.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] It is also possible to treat a local library (one that is not installed) as a package.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] For comparison, Vala itself uses an internal version of Gee.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] For details on how to generate this library, see the next section or the example.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] It is possible to use Autotools to create a library written in Vala.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] A library is created by using C code generated by Vala compiler, linked and installed as any other library.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Then you need tell which C files must be used to create the library and which of them must be distributable, allowing others to compile a tarball without Vala using standard Autotools commands: **configure**, **make** and **make install**.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] This example was taken from GXml recent additions.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] GXmlDom is a library aimed to have a GObject based libxml2 replacement; is written in Vala and originally used to use WAF to build.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Is important to add --pkg switches in order to valac to success and set all CFLAGS and LIBS required by the C library to compile and link against.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Vala is not yet capable of directly creating dynamic or static libraries.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] To create a library, proceed with the -c (compile only) switch and link the object files with your favourite linker, i.e. libtool or ar.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] $ valac -C ...(source files) $ gcc -o my-best-library.so --shared -fPIC ...(compiled C code files)...
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The following is an example of how to write a simple library in Vala, and also to compile and test it locally without having to install it first.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Save the following code to a file *test.vala*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] This is the actual library code, containing the functions we want to call from our main program.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Use the next command to generate *test.c*, *test.h* and *test.vapi* files.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] These are the C versions of the library to be compiled, and the VAPI file representing the library's public interface.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Save the following code to a file called *hello.vala*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] This is the code that will use the library we have created.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Now compile the application code, telling the compiler that we want to link against the library we just created.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] This command states that any required libraries will be found in the current directory.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] GIR files are XML descriptions of the API.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] VAPI files are descriptions of the public interface of external Vala libraries.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] When a library is written in Vala, this file is created by the Vala compiler, and basically an amalgamation of all public definitions from all Vala source files.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] For a library written in C, the VAPI file gets more complicated, particular if the naming conventions of the library do not follow the GLib convention.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The VAPI file will in this case contain many annotations describing how the standardised Vala interface mangles onto the C version.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] This process of creating this generally amounts to three steps, Running *vala-gen-introspect* to extract metadata from the C library.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Adding extra metadata to standardise the interface or make various other changes.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Generating a VAPI file from the above sources using *vapigen*.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The Vala distribution includes several programs to help you build and work with Vala applications.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] For more details of each tool, see the man pages.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] It's primary function is to transform Vala code into compilable C code.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] You can generally ignore warnings from the C compiler when using Vala and just need to notice the warnings from valac Vala has better information than the C compiler, so it knows certain things are valid when the C compiler has no way of knowing that.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Unfortunately we can't just add casts everywhere since there are situations where we can't generate a valid cast (and, what's more, no way to know what those situations are).
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] For example, compiling the Hello World will give us some warnings because valac by default generates code which is compatible with older versions of the GLib.Some methods may have been deprecated in your new version of GLib so that C language compiler will warn you.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Imagine a machine with older glib version want to run your vala program!
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The recommended approach is to just disable those warnings by passing options to the C compiler: $ valac -X -w hello.vala # Generated code is compatible, `-X` will pass `-w` to C compiler to disable all warnings.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] You could set a alias in your bash/zsh/fish shell.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The -o switch requests that an object file is created, rather than just outputting C source files.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The --pkg option says that this build needs information from the *gee-1.0* package.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] You do not need to specify details about what libraries to link in, the package has this information internally.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Finally, a list of source files is given.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] If you need a more complicated build process, use the -C switch to generate C files instead of a binary, and continue the process manually, or through a script.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] It creates a VAPI files from a library's metadata and any extra information required.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] vala-gen-introspect is a tool for extracting metainformation about GObject based libraries.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Nowadays, the preferred method is to use GObjectIntrospection instead, as vapigen can use GIR files directly.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] Vala programs can be debugged with the GNU Debugger gdb or one of its graphical front-ends, e.g.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] $ gdb debug-demo (gdb) run Starting program: /home/valacoder/debug-demo Program received signal SIGSEGV, Segmentation fault.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] GLib includes a large set of utilities, including wrappers for most of the standard libc functions and more.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] These tools are available on all Vala platforms, even those which are not POSIX compliant.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] For a complete description of all that GLib provides, see the GLib Reference Manual.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] That reference is related to the C API for GLib, but it is mainly very simple to work out how to translate into Vala.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] The APIs are not identical between C and Vala, but these naming rules should mean you can find the functions you need in the GLib VAPI files shipped with Vala, and from there find the parameters.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] This will hopefully suffice until more Vala documentation can be generated.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] For flexible file I/O and file handling see GIO Samples.
[src:vala-lang/vala-tutorial-p03] You can also use FileUtils.get_contents to load a file into a string.
